OpenKO Cooperative Protocol License (OCPL) Version 1.1
Copyright (c) 2026 OpenKO Contributors

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PREAMBLE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

This license governs software that implements, extends, or builds upon open
coordination protocols. Its purpose is to ensure that such software remains
permanently open, that users retain sovereignty over their identity and data,
and that no single actor can use technical or legal mechanisms to capture the
protocol, lock in users, or undermine federated governance.

Commercial activity built on top of this software is explicitly permitted and
encouraged. The conditions below protect the protocol's openness and users'
rights — they do not restrict legitimate business.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PERMISSIONS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Subject to the conditions below, every person is granted a worldwide,
royalty-free, non-exclusive, irrevocable license to:

  a. Use, copy, and distribute this software and its documentation.
  b. Modify this software and create derivative works.
  c. Build and operate commercial services using this software.
  d. Implement the protocol specifications published in the authoritative
     specification repository designated by the licensor.
  e. Charge for services, hosting, compute, agent labor, resource access,
     and any other commercial activity built on top of this software.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CONDITIONS
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Protocol Openness

   Any software that implements the protocols covered by this license must
   remain interoperable with the canonical protocol specifications published
   by the licensor. You may not use technical measures, patent claims,
   contractual restrictions, or any other mechanism to prevent third parties
   from implementing these specifications or from federating with nodes that
   run your software.

   Protocol specifications must remain publicly readable. You may not move
   them behind authentication, paywalls, or access controls.

2. Identity Sovereignty

   You may not modify this software to prevent users from:

     a. Exporting their identity documents, cryptographic key material, and
        all associated credentials in full, at any time, at no charge.
     b. Exporting their contribution history, reputation records, attestations,
        and participation data in a machine-readable open format.
     c. Migrating their identity and all associated data to another compatible
        implementation at any time, without penalty, delay, or data loss.
     d. Revoking all delegations and reclaiming full control over their agents,
        services, and authorization tokens.

3. Data Portability

   Any hosted service operating this software must, upon a user's written
   request, provide a complete machine-readable export of all data associated
   with that user within 30 days, at no charge. The export format must be
   documented and usable without this software.

4. No Lock-in

   You may not enforce any patent, trade secret, license term, or contractual
   restriction that would prevent a third party from:

     a. Implementing the protocol specifications covered by this license.
     b. Building software that reads or writes data formats defined by these
        specifications.
     c. Building a node that federates with nodes running your software.
     d. Forking this software and operating an independent network.

5. Constitutional Invariants

   You may not modify this software to circumvent or remove enforcement of
   the following principles:

     i.   No permanent central authority — no single node, organization, or
          individual may be granted irrevocable control over the network or
          its governance.
     ii.  Protocols remain open — all protocol specifications must remain
          publicly readable and freely implementable by any party.
     iii. Participation remains voluntary — no participant may be coerced
          into joining, remaining in, or contributing to the network.
     iv.  Contributions remain transparent — the record of who contributed
          what must be auditable by participants and verifiable by third parties.
     v.   Identities remain sovereign — participants control their own identity
          material; no operator may hold identity hostage.
     vi.  Knowledge remains portable — data and knowledge artifacts must be
          exportable in open formats at any time.
     vii. Governance remains federated — governance authority must be
          distributed across independent cells and federations; no single
          entity may capture the governance process.
     viii.AI systems remain auditable — automated agents operating in the
          network must expose their reasoning and actions to audit by their
          controllers and by governance.
     ix.  Local autonomy preserved — local cells and communities retain
          authority over their own operations within the constraints of
          protocol standards; no global authority may override local governance
          for local matters.
     x.   Public-good missions prioritized — the network's economic mechanisms
          must be designed to sustain public-good missions, not only
          commercially profitable ones.

6. Attribution

   All distributions must retain this license notice. User-visible
   documentation and hosted service interfaces must credit the originating
   project and this license. Attribution in the project's lineage record is
   permanent and survives stewardship transitions.

7. Patent Non-Aggression

   Any contributor to this software who holds patents that would be infringed
   by a conforming implementation of the covered protocol specifications grants
   a royalty-free, perpetual, irrevocable patent license to all parties for
   the purpose of implementing those specifications. This grant is not
   revocable and survives any transfer of the patent.

8. Source Availability for Network Services

   If you operate a publicly accessible service that uses a modified version
   of this software, you must make the complete corresponding source of your
   modifications available to users of that service under the terms of this
   license, without charge, via a publicly accessible repository or download.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DEPENDENCY BOUNDARY
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The conditions of this license apply to the covered work itself. They do not
apply to libraries, dependencies, or other software components that the
covered work incorporates or links against, provided those components are
distributed under their own applicable licenses and are not modifications of
the covered work.

A covered work may incorporate components licensed under MIT, Apache 2.0,
GPL v2 or later, LGPL v2.1 or later, AGPL v3, MPL 2.0, or other open-source
licenses without those components becoming subject to the conditions of this
license beyond their own terms. The conditions of this license apply only to
the portions of the work originally licensed under the OCPL.

